{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"96ec9964-56d7-4486-9dcb-22850bfc282c","content":"No files found in the working directory. I'll provide the solution directly.\n\n## Converting to Compiled Bindings\n\nAdd `x:DataType` to your `ContentPage` to enable compiled bindings:\n\n```xml\n<?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"utf-8\" ?>\n<ContentPage xmlns=\"http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui\"\n             xmlns:x=\"http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml\"\n             xmlns:vm=\"clr-namespace:YourApp.ViewModels\"\n             x:Class=\"YourApp.Views.SettingsPage\"\n             x:DataType=\"vm:SettingsViewModel\">\n\n    <VerticalStackLayout Padding=\"20\" Spacing=\"15\">\n\n        <Entry Text=\"{Binding Theme}\"\n               Placeholder=\"Theme\" />\n\n        <Switch IsToggled=\"{Binding NotificationsEnabled}\" />\n\n        <Stepper Value=\"{Binding FontSize}\"\n                 Minimum=\"8\"\n                 Maximum=\"32\" />\n\n        <Label Text=\"{Binding FontSize, StringFormat='Font Size: {0}'}\" />\n\n    </VerticalStackLayout>\n</ContentPage>\n```\n\n**Key changes:**\n1. Added `xmlns:vm` pointing to your ViewModel namespace.\n2. Added `x:DataType=\"vm:SettingsViewModel\"` on the `ContentPage`.\n\n## Catching Binding Errors at Build Time\n\nCompiled bindings are validated by the XAML compiler. To ensure errors surface at build time:\n\n**1. Enable strict mode in your `.csproj`:**\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n    <!-- Treats XAML warnings (including binding mismatches) as errors -->\n    <WarningsAsErrors>XC0045;XC0022</WarningsAsErrors>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n**2. What gets caught:**\n- Typos in property names (e.g., `{Binding Themee}`) → compile error\n- Type mismatches (e.g., binding `FontSize` to a `string`-only control)\n- Missing properties on the declared `x:DataType`\n\n**3. If you need to opt out for a subtree** (e.g., dynamic data):\n```xml\n<CollectionView x:DataType=\"{x:Null}\" ... />\n```\n\nWith `x:DataType` set, the XAML compiler resolves bindings at compile time instead of using reflection at runtime — giving you both error detection and better performance.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"6320ccd9-1a1e-412b-9eeb-6cb374c493bd","outputTokens":593,"requestId":"A85A:2AD648:653866:74C9A2:69FBE1D3"},"id":"db890005-71bb-43a7-be72-be399d21ab3f","timestamp":"2026-05-07T00:50:40.096Z","parentId":"7c72b5a4-22c8-41fc-91eb-e3c58bd5d543"}
